data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow + ResetAbort

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill work that exceeds a deadline, catches `ThreadAbortException` to suppress the abort, and calls `Thread.ResetAbort()`. All three APIs throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),   // wrap legacy work that can't check the token
            timeout);
    }

    // Preferred overload — work cooperates with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates from Task.Run
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

---

### What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Tasks use the thread pool; avoids raw thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OCE`, not `TAE` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't forcibly inject exceptions |

---

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
The old code forcibly killed the thread mid-execution. The new code *requests* cancellation — if `work` ignores the token, it keeps running in the background even after `TimeoutException` is thrown. This is the biggest behavioral difference.

```csharp
// BAD — ignores the token, runs forever on timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(_ =>
{
    while (true) { /* CPU-bound work */ }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// GOOD — checks the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // do a chunk of work
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.**
Forgetting `using` leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using` or dispose in `finally`.

**3. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.**
The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout — not an unrelated cancellation from upstream code.

**4. Truly uncooperative code cannot be cancelled in-process.**
If `work` calls a blocking native API or third-party code that will never check the token, your only option is to run it in a **separate process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
